1 Background

library(cellmig)
library(ggplot2)
library(ggforce)
library(patchwork)
ggplot2::theme_set(new = theme_bw(base_size = 10))

2 Data (raw)

In this vignette we will use simulated data:

  • 6 compounds (chemical): c-1, c-2, , c-6
  • 5 doses: 1, 2, 3, 4 and 5
  • 3 sample: s-1, s-2 and s-3
  • 2 batches: b-1 and b-2

In each sample from a combination of compound x dose x batch, we have 20 observations (cell velocities \(v\))

data("d", package = "cellmig")
knitr::kable(d[1:10,], row.names = F, digits = 2)
v sample compound dose group plate
2.03 w1 c1 d1 c1|d1 p1
3.21 w1 c1 d1 c1|d1 p1
2.00 w1 c1 d1 c1|d1 p1
5.60 w1 c1 d1 c1|d1 p1
4.80 w1 c1 d1 c1|d1 p1
2.55 w1 c1 d1 c1|d1 p1
1.20 w1 c1 d1 c1|d1 p1
1.07 w1 c1 d1 c1|d1 p1
3.07 w1 c1 d1 c1|d1 p1
2.44 w1 c1 d1 c1|d1 p1 
ggplot(data = d)+
  facet_wrap(facets = ~paste0("compound=", compound), scales = "free_y", ncol = 2)+
  geom_sina(aes(x = as.factor(dose), col = plate, y = v, group = sample), size = 0.5)+
  theme_bw()+
  theme(legend.position = "top",
        strip.text.x = element_text(margin = margin(0.03,0,0.03,0, "cm")))+
  xlab(label = "dose")+
  ylab(label = "migration speed")+
  scale_color_manual(values = c("steelblue", "orange", "forestgreen", "purple"))+
  guides(color = guide_legend(override.aes = list(size = 3)))

3 Migration speed (scaled)

ggplot(data = d)+
  facet_wrap(facets = ~paste0("compound=", compound), scales = "free_y", ncol = 2)+
  geom_sina(aes(x = as.factor(dose), col = plate, y = v/max(v), group = sample), size = 0.5)+
  theme_bw()+
  theme(legend.position = "top",
        strip.text.x = element_text(margin = margin(0.03,0,0.03,0, "cm")))+
  xlab(label = "dose")+
  ylab(label = "migration speed [scaled by max speed]")+
  scale_color_manual(values = c("steelblue", "orange", "forestgreen", "purple"))+
  guides(color = guide_legend(override.aes = list(size = 3)))

4 Model fitting

o <- cellmig(x = d,
             control = list(mcmc_warmup = 300,
                            mcmc_steps = 1300,
                            mcmc_chains = 4,
                            mcmc_cores = 4,
                            mcmc_algorithm = "NUTS",
                            adapt_delta = 0.8,
                            max_treedepth = 10))

5 What are the overall effects of compounds and doses on cell migration?

ggplot(data = o$s$mu_group)+
  geom_line(aes(x = dose, y = mean, col = compound, group = compound))+
  geom_point(aes(x = dose, y = mean, col = compound))+
  geom_errorbar(aes(x = dose, y = mean, ymin = X2.5., ymax = X97.5., 
                    col = compound), width = 0.04)+
  ylab(label = "effect")

6 Compare the dose-response profiles for different compounds

get_profiles(x = o)+
  patchwork::plot_layout(widths = c(1, 1, 5))

7 Compare the effects between treatment group

7.1 Pairwise dot-plot comparison \(\rightarrow\) x minus y axis

  • x/y-axis treatment groups (combinations of compounds and doses)
  • \(\delta\): Difference between treatment groups at y-x axis.
  • \(\pi\): probability of seing either completely positive or negative \(\delta\)
u <- get_pairs(x = o)
u$plot

7.2 Violin plot based targeted comparison

  • x/y-axis treatment groups (combinations of compounds and doses)
  • \(\delta\): Difference between treatment groups at y-x axis.
  • \(\pi\): probability of seing either completely positive or negative \(\delta\)
u <- get_violins(x = o, 
                 from_groups = c("c1|d1", "c1|d2", "c1|d3", "c1|d4", "c1|d5"), 
                 to_group = "c2|d1")
u$plot

8 Posterior predictive checks (PPCs)

g <- get_ppc(x = o)
g

9 migcell can be used to simulate data

sim_data <- sim(N_well_cells = 20, 
                N_plate = 3,
                N_group = 6,
                N_well_reps = 3,
                shape = 4,
                sigma_bplate = 0.3,
                sigma_wplate = 0.1,
                alpha_plate = c(1, 1.2, 1),
                mu_group = c(-1, -0.5, -0, 0.5, 1, 2))
